    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-08-20T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-08-20T04:00:00-05:00" n="334"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d334">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.515 Silver/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-08-20T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 20, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 20—9:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>372. Have been requested by Dr. H. H. Kung, Minister of Finance, to transmit by
                    cable to President Roosevelt, the following in paraphrase: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>The London silver agreement of July 1933<note n="23" xml:id="d334fn23">
                                <ref target="frus1933v01#pg_763">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1933, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 763</ref>.</note> received the
                            signature of China’s representative and has more recently been ratified
                            by the <pb facs="0531" n="441" xml:id="pg_441"/> National Government of
                            the Republic of China with the understanding that its major purpose was
                            to assure the stability of the price of silver which was thought menaced
                            by the large surplus stocks held by the Government of India and Spain.
                            The preamble of the agreement states in part that it is to the advantage
                            of China that sales from monetary stocks of silver be offset by
                            purchases as herein provided, with a view to its effective
                            stabilization.</p>
                        <p>It now appears that under the Silver Purchase Act of 1934<note n="24"
                                xml:id="d334fn24">Approved June 19, 1934; 48 Stat. 1178.</note> the
                            stability of the price of silver and the interests of China are as much
                            menaced as by the previous situation of potential sellers. China would
                            therefore appreciate an indication of the probable policy of the United
                            States in the future purchase of silver in order that China may properly
                            safeguard her currency, which has recently been flowing out of the
                            country to a degree that is potentially alarming.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
